  &lt;p id="dmLwKx"&gt;2024 is almost over, and it has been a &lt;em&gt;year. &lt;/em&gt;The tech world has been shaken up a hundred times over, it seems: there was the splashy &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24054862/apple-vision-pro-review-vr-ar-headset-features-price"&gt;Vision Pro launch&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/23869483/us-v-google-search-antitrust-case-updates"&gt;Google being declared a monopoly&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/10/10/24266333/ai-agents-assistants-openai-google-deepmind-bots"&gt;endless AI hype&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24279103/2024-election-guide-trump-harris-policy-issues"&gt;hugely consequential US election&lt;/a&gt;, the ongoing &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/11/22/24302735/elon-musk-doge-vivek-ramaswamy-rage-curtis-yarvin"&gt;political ascendance of Elon Musk&lt;/a&gt;, and another generation of gadgets &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24126502/humane-ai-pin-review"&gt;trying and failing to replace your smartphone&lt;/a&gt;. The industry looks different than it did in January; so does our relationship with technology. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="EoagOz"&gt;There’s still a month to go, and we’re not remotely ready to declare this year’s tech news dead and gone, but given that it’s a holiday weekend in the US we figured it might be time for a look back. (Hope you had a great Thanksgiving, by the way!)&lt;/p&gt;
